<li id="cite_note-40"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Soares-Cunha, Carina; Coimbra, Bárbara; Domingues, Ana Verónica; Vasconcelos, Nivaldo; Sousa, Nuno; Rodrigues, Ana João (19 April 2018). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5957524">"Nucleus Accumbens Microcircuit Underlying D2-MSN-Driven Increase in Motivation"</a>. <i>eNeuro</i>. <b>5</b> (2): ENEURO.0386–18.2018. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1523%2FENEURO.0386-18.2018">10.1523/ENEURO.0386-18.2018</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Central" title="PubMed Central">PMC</a>&#160;<span class="cs1-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5957524">5957524</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29780881">29780881</a>. <q>Importantly, optogenetic activation of D2-MSN terminals in the VP was sufficient to recapitulate the motivation enhancement. In summary, our data suggests that optogenetic stimulation of NAc D2-MSNs indirectly modulates VTA dopaminergic activity, contributing for increased motivation.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=eNeuro&amp;rft.atitle=Nucleus+Accumbens+Microcircuit+Underlying+D2-MSN-Driven+Increase+in+Motivation&amp;rft.volume=5&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=ENEURO.0386-18.2018&amp;rft.date=2018-04-19&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC5957524&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F29780881&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1523%2FENEURO.0386-18.2018&amp;rft.aulast=Soares-Cunha&amp;rft.aufirst=Carina&amp;rft.au=Coimbra%2C