<li id="cite_note-78"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-78">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Treadway, MT; Zald, DH (January 2011). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3005986">"Reconsidering anhedonia in depression: lessons from translational neuroscience"</a>. <i>Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews</i>. <b>35</b> (3): 537–55. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1016%2Fj.neubiorev.2010.06.006">10.1016/j.neubiorev.2010.06.006</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Central" title="PubMed Central">PMC</a>&#160;<span class="cs1-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3005986">3005986</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20603146">20603146</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Neuroscience+and+Biobehavioral+Reviews&amp;rft.atitle=Reconsidering+anhedonia+in+depression%3A+lessons+from+translational+neuroscience&amp;rft.volume=35&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=537-55&amp;rft.date=2011-01&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC3005986&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F20603146&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.neubiorev.2010.06.006&amp;rft.aulast=Treadway&amp;rft.aufirst=MT&amp;rft.au=Zald%2C+DH&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC3005986&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-79"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-79">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Walsh, JJ; Han, MH (12 December 2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4339667">"The heterogeneity of ventral tegmental area neurons: Projection functions in a mood-related context"</a>. <i>Neuroscience</i>. <b>282</b>: 101–8. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1016%2Fj.neuroscience.2014.06.006">10.1016/j.neuroscience.2014.06.006</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Central" title="PubMed Central">PMC</a>&#160;<span class="cs1-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4339667">4339667</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24931766">24931766</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Neuroscience&amp;rft.atitle=The+heterogeneity+of+ventral+tegmental+area+neurons%3A+Projection+functions+in+a+mood-related+context&amp;rft.volume=282&amp;rft.pages=101-8&amp;rft.date=2014-12-12&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC4339667&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F24931766&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.neuroscience.2014.06.006&amp;rft.aulast=Walsh&amp;rft.aufirst=JJ&amp;rft.au=Han%2C+MH&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC4339667&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-80"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-80">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Lammel, S; Lim, BK; Malenka, RC (January 2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3778102">"Reward and aversion in a heterogeneous midbrain dopamine system"</a>. <i>Neuropharmacology</i>. 76 Pt B: 351–9. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1016%2Fj.neuropharm.2013.03.019">10.1016/j.neuropharm.2013.03.019</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Central" title="PubMed Central">PMC</a>&#160;<span class="cs1-lock-free" title="Freely accessible"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3778102">3778102</a></span>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23578393">23578393</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Neuropharmacology&amp;rft.atitle=Reward+and+aversion+in+a+heterogeneous+midbrain+dopamine+system&amp;rft.volume=76+Pt+B&amp;rft.pages=351-9&amp;rft.date=2014-01&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC3778102&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F23578393&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.neuropharm.2013.03.019&amp;rft.aulast=Lammel&amp;rft.aufirst=S&amp;rft.au=Lim%2C+BK&amp;rft.au=Malenka%2C+RC&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC3778102&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-81"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-81">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Knowland, D; Lim, BK (5 January 2018). "Circuit-based frameworks of depressive behaviors: The role of reward circuitry and beyond". <i>Pharmacology Biochemistry and Behavior</i>. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1016%2Fj.pbb.2017.12.010">10.1016/j.pbb.2017.12.010</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29309799">29309799</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Pharmacology+Biochemistry+and+Behavior&amp;rft.atitle=Circuit-based+frameworks+of+depressive+behaviors%3A+The+role+of+reward+circuitry+and+beyond&amp;rft.date=2018-01-05&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.pbb.2017.12.010&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F29309799&amp;rft.aulast=Knowland&amp;rft.aufirst=D&amp;rft.au=Lim%2C+BK&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Lammel2014b-82"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Lammel2014b_82-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Lammel2014b_82-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Lammel, S; Tye, KM; Warden, MR (January 2014). "Progress in understanding mood disorders: optogenetic dissection of neural circuits". <i>Genes, Brain, and Behavior</i>. <b>13</b> (1): 38–51. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1111%2Fgbb.12049">10.1111/gbb.12049</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23682971">23682971</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Genes%2C+Brain%2C+and+Behavior&amp;rft.atitle=Progress+in+understanding+mood+disorders%3A+optogenetic+dissection+of+neural+circuits&amp;rft.volume=13&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=38-51&amp;rft.date=2014-01&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fgbb.12049&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F23682971&amp;rft.aulast=Lammel&amp;rft.aufirst=S&amp;rft.au=Tye%2C+KM&amp;rft.au=Warden%2C+MR&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-83"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-83">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Bucci, P; Galderisi, S (May 2017). "Categorizing and assessing negative symptoms". <i>Current Opinion in Psychiatry</i>. <b>30</b> (3): 201–208. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1097%2FYCO.0000000000000322">10.1097/YCO.0000000000000322</a>. <a href="/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" class="mw-redirect" title="PubMed Identifier">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28212174">28212174</a>. <q>They also provide a separate assessment of the consummatory anhedonia (reduced experience of pleasure derived from ongoing enjoyable activities) and anticipatory anhedonia (reduced ability to anticipate future pleasure). In fact, the former one seems to be relatively intact in schizophrenia, whereas the latter one seems to be impaired [32 – 34]. However, discrepant data have also been reported [35].</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Current+Opinion+in+Psychiatry&amp;rft.atitle=Categorizing+and+assessing+negative+symptoms&amp;rft.volume=30&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=201-208&amp;rft.date=2017-05&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1097%2FYCO.0000000000000322&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F28212174&amp;rft.aulast=Bucci&amp;rft.aufirst=P&amp;rft.au=Galderisi%2C+S&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEYoung2018215a-84"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEYoung2018215a_84-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFYoung2018215a">Young &amp; 2018 215a</a>,"Several recent reviews (e.g., Cohen and Minor, 2010) have found that individuals with schizophrenia show relatively intact self-reported emotional responses to affect-eliciting stimuli as well as other indicators of intact response...A more mixed picture arises from functional neuroimaging studies examining brain responses to other types of pleasurable stimuli in schizophrenia (Paradiso et al., 2003)"</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEYoung2018215b-85"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEYoung2018215b_85-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFYoung2018215b">Young &amp; 2018 215b</a>,"As such it is surprising that behavioral studies have suggested that reinforcement learning is intact in schizophrenia when learning is relatively implicit (though, see Siegert et al., 2008 for evidence of impaired Serial Reaction Time task learning), but more impaired when explicit representations of stimulus-reward contingencies are needed (see Gold et al., 2008). This pattern has given rise to the theory that the striatally mediated gradual reinforcement learning system may be intact in schizophrenia, while more rapid, on-line, cortically mediated learning systems are impaired."</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-FOOTNOTEYoung2018216-86"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FOOTNOTEYoung2018216_86-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFYoung2018216">Young &amp; 2018 216</a>, "We have recently shown that individuals with schizophrenia can show improved cognitive control performance when information about rewards are externally presented but not when they must be internally maintained (Mann et al., 2013), with some evidence for impairments in DLPFC and striatal activation during internal maintenance of reward information being associated with individuals’ differences in motivation (Chung and Barch, 2016)."</span>
</li>
</ol></div>
<ul><li><cite class="citation book">Young, Jared W.; Anticevic, Alan; Barch, Deanna M. (2018). "Cognitive and Motivational Neuroscience of Psychotic Disorders".  In Charney, Dennis S.; Sklar, Pamela; Buxbaum, Joseph D.; Nestler, Eric J. <i>Charney &amp; Nestler's Neurobiology of Mental Illness</i> (5th ed.). New York: Oxford University Press. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780190681425" title="Special:BookSources/9780190681425">9780190681425</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Cognitive+and+Motivational+Neuroscience+of+Psychotic+Disorders&amp;rft.btitle=Charney+%26+Nestler%27s+Neurobiology+of+Mental+Illness&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.edition=5th&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2018&amp;rft.isbn=9780190681425&amp;rft.aulast=Young&amp;rft.aufirst=Jared+W.&amp;rft.au=Anticevic%2C+Alan&amp;rft.au=Barch%2C+Deanna+M.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AReward+system" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886058088"/></li></ul>
